Our strategy for [cultivating](mission) an economy of gratitude, generosity,
and love is to take advantage of the **open source value vacuum** to fill the
market with **open organizations**.


## Open Organizations

[*The Open Organization*](https://www.amazon.com/-/dp/1625275277) is a book by
Jim Whitehurst documenting Red Hat's company culture. Red Hat hosts an [ongoing
conversation](https://opensource.com/open-organization) about the book and its
themes via their website, OpenSource.com. Prior to Jim's book, Gratipay talked
about [open
companies](https://gratipay.news/the-second-open-company-4cbab7ca1a47), but
with Red Hat stepping forward with so much more momentum, we've folded our
efforts into theirs.

Open organizations as Gratipay defines them have four characteristics:

1. **transparent decisions**&mdash;the default is for information to be shared
   publicly and decisions to be vetted publicly before being finalized;
1. **open hiring**&mdash;anyone can start collaborating of their own volition, no
   permission necessary to get started;
1. **take-what-you-want compensation**&mdash;individuals have agency to reap a
   meaningful economic benefit from their collaboration; and
1. **pay-what-you-want revenue**&mdash;labor and profits are funded by voluntary
   payments, not hard fees.

Each of these is highly nuanced in practice, and can be implemented somewhat
independently of the others. The purpose behind each is to emphasize the agency
of the individual over the group. Lack of agency leads to resentment and guilt.
But when there is personal agency, gratitude and generosity are able to
flourish.


## The Open Source Value Vacuum

We aim to evolve open organizations from open source software projects, because
open source software projects are the best-established existing institutions
that are closest to our vision of the open organization. Transparent
decision-making and open &ldquo;hiring&rdquo; are the norm. Insofar as they
have any revenue, it is voluntary. There's historically not been much revenue,
however, so practices around compensation are not well-developed (hence the
scare quotes around &ldquo;hiring&rdquo;). 

In economic terms, open source software is a [*public
good*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_good#Definition_matrix):

![goods matrix](matrix.png)

There are three ways to fit public goods into the economy:

1. **Enclosure**. In other words, taking goods out of the commons, making them
   excludable. Booooorrriiinnngg!

1. **Taxation**. This is akin to enclosure, in that both involve *forcing* people
   to pay for the thing.

1. **Persuasion**. The pitch is mostly enlightened self-interest with a
sprinkling of altruism. This is us! &#x1f483;

Persuading customers to pay for value they may also access for free is an
&ldquo;extreme&rdquo; solution to the [value capture
problem](https://hbr.org/2014/10/capture-more-value):

> Taking this idea to an extreme, some companies have *pay what you want*
> arrangements, whereby the seller must take whatever the customer offers.
> Given the potential for free-rider abuse, few businesses contemplate this
> innovation.

Free-rider abuse is the [classic
difficulty](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free-rider_problem) in providing
public goods, and it is intrinsic to open source. &ldquo;The
license shall not require a royalty or other fee,&rdquo; is the [very first
article](https://opensource.org/definition) of the open source definition, and
freedom-as-in-beer was the primary driver for corporate open source adoption
[until 2011](https://www.blackducksoftware.com/2016-future-of-open-source)
(slide 10). One of the great strengths of open source is also perhaps its
greatest weaknesses.

How much value is open source leaving on the table? 

The global economy is nominally
[$78T/y](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gross_world_product), and tech accounts
for
[$3T](https://go.forrester.com/blogs/16-01-05-global_tech_market_will_continue_to_grow_at_4_5_rates_in_2016_and_2017/)
(4%) of that.
[78%](http://www.zdnet.com/article/its-an-open-source-world-78-percent-of-companies-run-open-source-software/)
of companies use open source, so let's mark those down to $60.8T and $2.3T
respectively. Using open source in tech companies increases value by
[21%](https://medium.com/@nayafia/open-source-was-worth-at-least-143m-of-instagram-s-1b-acquisition-808bb85e4681),
so call that $475B of annual value created by open source in tech ($2.3T
&times; 21%). Non-tech companies still use [lots of
software](https://a16z.com/2016/08/20/why-software-is-eating-the-world/); let's
estimate that open source creates 2.1% of their value: that's another $1.2T
(($60.8T - $2.3T) &times; 2.1%). Open source creates $1.7T/y of value.

Volunteers produce
[half](http://dirkriehle.com/2013/08/22/paid-vs-volunteer-work-in-open-source/)
of open source, thereby adding $853B/y of value to the global economy. Open
source foundations receive \_\_\_\_\_ in funding capturing 0.001% of the value
created, and leaving 99.99% on the table.

While open source now finds that it painted itself into an economic corner, the
sheer size of the value created by open source makes it worthwhile to attempt
to increase the amount captured. 

Gratipay's strategic plan is to persuade companies to pay for open source
software.


