Open source has created a tremendous
amount of value while capturing almost none of it. Because of the size of the
value creation function, even a fractional increase in the capture function
will be interesting.




This creates some pressure to compensate open source projects *after* the fact
rather than beforehand. Is it enough?

Here are the specific points of leverage we see:

- **Risk management**. Open source is an upstream supplier for most companies.
  Insolvent vendors are risky (see:
[Heartbleed](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heartbleed#Root_causes.2C_possible_lessons.2C_and_reactions)).

- **Developer relations**. Companies with a good reputation in open source
  communities find it easier to hire from those communities.

- **Marketing**. Some companies are also trying to sell to developers.

- **Metrics**. Open source program directors want information about how their
  organizations consume open source.

- **Diversity in tech**. This is a
  [problem](http://www.npr.org/sections/money/2014/10/17/356944145/episode-576-when-women-stopped-coding)
worth addressing in its own right, and it dovetails with the idea of
proactively giving individuals agency to be involved in the engines of our
economy.

The goal is to tap these pressure points to get some funding moving into open
organizations. If we get enough money moving in this direction then we might
even [see](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kWH3Waigi5Y#t=5h59m17s) a new
[sector](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_sector#By_ownership) of the
economy: public, private, voluntary, &hellip; and open! And if we do that,
hopefully we'll have increased the gratitude and generosity in the world by a
fraction of a degree&mdash;maybe enough to get an interesting feedback loop
going!
